<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Public expenditure on health and social care</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from About </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> UK (PEX 0020)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:22pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">About </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> UK</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#af1e2d; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> UK is a charity set up to help the 6.5 million people who care for family or friends. At some point in our lives every one of us will be involved in looking after an older relative, a sick friend or a disabled family member. Whilst caring is part and parcel of life, it can affect your job, your health and your finances. Without the right support the personal costs can be high.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> UK is a membership </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">organisation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, run by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. We have 17,000 members and a reach of many more. </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">We provide information and advice about caring alongside practical and emotional support for </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">carers</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">. </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">Carers</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> UK also campaigns to make life better for </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">carers</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> and influences policy makers, employers and service providers, to help them improve </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">carers'</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> lives.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> UK’s advice and information services answer around 16,000 queries from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and professionals every year. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Our website is viewed by over 100,000 people every month, 27,000 subscribe to our monthly email newsletters, and the combined reach of our online communities and social networks exceeds 38,000. We’re in regular contact with around 1,500 local </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, including many run by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, who are in touch with around 950,000 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> UK has offices in Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland. This response reflects the views of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">organisation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, UK-wide.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:22pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> UK believes that funding decisions about the health and care system need to consider the role of family and the impact that the health and social care system has on it. The system is not currently sustainable for families and will become increasingly untenable if it does not adapt and change to accommodate our evolving demographic structures.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> UK is calling for a duty on NHS bodies to identify </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. As well as ensuring that family members are quickly involved when they need to be and their needs are considered, it would help to change the perception of many NHS bodies to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and achieve the practical as well as cultural shift that we are seeking.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We would like to see a fundamental shift in attitude towards the use of technology and the opportunities that it brings in managing care, for individuals, families and the NHS and social care systems. Health and social care also need to explore confidentiality so that information can be given to families and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> when needed.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Lower the level of national eligibility criteria to include moderate needs for care and support.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Expand funding for preventive services in the community.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Align more closely the responsibilities that local authorities and the NHS have for meeting the needs of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Increase funding for areas of social care that are free at the point of delivery to aid joint working where common goals align. These services include </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">reablement</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, prevention around hospital admissions, public health services and end of life care in particular.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Further integration could be generated by placing on the NHS, a similar well-being duty as contained in the Clause 1 of the Care Bill.  This would also help to align priorities across the two bodies and associated planning bodies</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Government should consider the economic impact of the operation of the current arrangements across health and social care in order to drive changes which are better for families, business and the economy.   </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Increased care coordination is a priority, with care coordinators and information sharing underpinned by technology and understanding of the role and input of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. We believe that some of the ideas emerging from the Future Hospitals Commission by the Royal College of Physicians would help this.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">More pooling of funding and a re-examination of the funding and tariff structures that promote coordination and efficiency. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:22pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The impact on the provision of adult social care of the 2010 spending review settlement and the ability of local authorities to make the necessary efficiency savings</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Publically funded social care continues to be tightly rationed and despite the rise in the number of older people and the number of children with complex needs living into adulthood, the number of people accessing social care is going down.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">NHS Information Centre figures</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> show that the “</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">total number of people receiving services in 2012-13 was 1.3m (down 9% from 2011-12 and down 25% from 2007-08). Of these, 1.1m received community based services (a fall of 10% from 2011-12), 209,000 received residential care (a fall of 2% from 2011-12) and 87,000 received nursing care (which is less than a 1% change from 2011-12). Feedback from councils suggests that the fall this year is again due to a number of reasons including raised eligibility criteria for services and reduced funding/resources within Councils with Adult Social Services Responsibilities, but also the contribution of an increase in the provision of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">reablement</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> services outside of a formal assessment process.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Families are increasingly bridging this gap in funding and social care support by providing greater amounts of care themselves. The latest Census results tell us that there are 6.5 million </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> throughout the UK. There are 1.3 million who are providing 50 hours of care or more per week. This number providing substantial amounts of care has been on a steady increase from 1985, and continues to rise much more rapidly than the total </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carer</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> population – a 35% increase compared to an 11% rise in the total </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carer</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> population.  This is occurring at the same time as a shift towards community-based care moves NHS responsibilities to local councils yet the amount of social care provided is decreasing relative to the number of people who need it.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">    </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The care provided by family and loved ones is unpaid but it does come at a cost to the finances and health of the families involved and to the wider economy.  Family and close friends who provide care are a vital and critical part of the health and social care system, but continue to be overlooked and often taken for granted.  Without better support for families from health and social services, the ability of many </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to provide care is threatened.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">By 2050 globally three times more people of working age will be looking after two billion ageing family members</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">– and the majority will have to combine that care with paid work. There is not a ready “pool” of family members who are ready and able to take on an increased level of caring without significant consequences for their own health and well-being, ability to work and short and long term personal finances.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The health and social care system needs to invest more in supporting and sustaining families who care and integrate and align the ways it works to meet the needs of whole families.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:22pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Reports of particular financial pressures in the system, such as funding for General Practice, and for Accident and Emergency services and the impact on NHS plans of decisions currently being made by local authorities and the use of the additional funding for social care being made available through the NHS budget</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">he impact on the NHS of social care services which are unable to properly support families can be seen in emergency admissions to hospital and readmission after discharge.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Carers UK’s State of Caring survey of over 3,900 carers,</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> asked a wide range of questions about their experiences of caring. 55% of survey respondents said that the person they care for has been admitted to emergency hospital services in the last three years.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Many survey respondents attributed emergency admissions to a lack of support.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Whilst 64% of survey respondents did not believe that the emergency admission of their loved one could have been prevented, significant percentages identified areas where additional support could have prevented admission:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.87pt; padding-left:3.68pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">17% of respondents said more support from care services could have prevented emergency admission</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">6% said replacement care (for when they, the carer, needs medical treatment)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">21% said higher quality care and support for the person they care for</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">9% said </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">adaptions</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in the home of the person they care for</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.87pt; padding-left:3.68pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">6% said </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">telecare</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> or </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">telehealth</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (e.g. monitoring equipment, alarms and sensors) could have prevented the need to go into hospital. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This evidence shows that greater and higher quality support from care services could have a significant impact on the number of emergency admissions to hospital.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">4.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The most recent survey from the Association of Directors of Adult Social Care annual survey of suggests that in the three years since the beginning of the current austerity </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, some £2.68 billion savings will have been made by adult social care - 20 per cent of net spending.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">4.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">These spending reductions mean that millions of older and disabled people are unable to access care to meet ‘moderate’ needs for care and support. Age UK in its Care in Crisis report has estimated that of 2 million older people in England with care-related needs nearly 800,000 receive no support from public or private sector agencies” and found a £500 million shortfall in social care funding</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">4.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A number of charities representing working age disabled people have made similar calculations and found that social care for working age disabled adults is underfunded by at least £1.2 billion</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  They also estimate that 69,000 disabled people with 'moderate needs' are not currently receiving support, meaning they are likely to struggle with day-to-day life</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">4.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In making decisions about the balance of future funding for the health and social care systems, the Government must seriously consider the impact on the NHS of the current crisis in social care funding. Earlier investment to meet lower level needs and enable the management of long-term conditions can prevent or delay the development of needs which may require a greater level of care and be more likely to require acute care.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">4.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Under current proposals local authorities would fund substantial care only and only the cost of meeting substantial needs will count towards the cap on care costs. A lower eligibility criteria would act as an important lever in preventing the development of need for care and support.  There is an economic case for making the change. Economic modeling on four different service types carried out by Deloitte in 2013 found that for every £1 spent on support for people with ‘moderate’ level needs, an average of £1.30 will be saved in the NHS, local and central government</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">4.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The wider cost to the economy of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> being pushed out of the workforce are significant.  Research from the LSE Personal Social Services Research Unit has estimated that the public expenditure costs of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> leaving employment is £1.3 billion per year</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. Further work from Age UK based on these figures suggests that when lost earnings are taken into account this rises to £5.3 billion</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">4.9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">However, if the Government puts in place eligibility set at substantial it is vital that local authorities have adequate funding to put in place free or affordable preventative services such as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">telecare</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and adaptations.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">4.10</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Without a bigger funding commitment for preventative services and services which enable people and their families to manage long-term conditions, disabled and older people and their families will continue to struggle without proper support until their needs escalate to a high and expensive level.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">4.11</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In relation to General Practice, there are high-impact, low-cost measures which GP surgeries can put in place to make a significant contribution to prevention. GP surgeries are often the first and most regular point of contact for families affected by disability and ill health. Their role in identifying individuals with caring responsibilities and signposting them to information and support – particularly advice on their rights and entitlements to financial and practical support – can result in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> accessing support far earlier and preventing them from reaching breaking point. However </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> UK’s State of Caring research 2013 showed that 67% of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> say that their GP is aware of their caring responsibilities but gives them no extra help</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">4.12</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> UK’s Local GP Ambassadors, volunteer </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and former </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, demonstrate how change can be delivered through partnership work with local support groups and advice agencies to embed </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carer</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">-identification and signposting. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> UK continues to argue that the best driver of change would be a duty on NHS bodies to identify </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and promote their wellbeing. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:22pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Progress on making efficiencies through the integration of health and social care services.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">5.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Some of the most significant problems that are caused for families can stem from lack of coordination between different services within the health service and social care, and this extends into housing, work, benefits and other related entitlements. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">5.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Being passed from one department to another, being asked to repeat their medical history and struggling to get the right treatment from a complex and fragmented health and care system are all common experiences of patients. It is often families and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> who take on the role of trying to navigate this system. Therefore, the principle recently suggested by the Department of Health of having one accountable person, for every older person receiving care, who has an in-depth knowledge of how the whole care system works and who can coordinate and bring together different services and treatments is a very welcome idea. In Kensington and Chelsea, for example, there is commissioning of link workers that go into GP practices to offer to link up with the rest of the services that families need.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">5.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A fundamental shift is needed in the perspective of the NHS in relation to supporting families. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> UK is proposing a target duty on health bodies to identify </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and promote the health and well-being of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> as a strategic role. This would also help to redress the huge imbalance in rights and attitudes.  With social care moving towards fully integrated </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carers’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> rights, the NHS meanwhile has no duty of care towards the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carer</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, apart from when they are a patient in their own right. It is critical to align these duties by introducing new legislation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">5.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Data remains a significant barrier to integration of health and social care.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Health and social care also need to explore confidentiality so that information can be given to families and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> when needed. Coupled with new technology that enables </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to see care records updated, support families to co-ordinate caring and care services, this could </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">revolutionise</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> families’ ability to care. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> United Nations, Department for Economic and Social Affairs Population Division, 2007, World Population Ageing</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> Supporting Working Carers: The benefits to families, business and the economy, Carers UK, Employers for Carers and HM Government, August 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> State of Caring Survey 2013 final data.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> 76% of these admissions were due to deterioration of health and 35% were due to an accident or fall (respondents were able to choose multiple options if appropriate)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> www.adass.org.uk/index.php?option=com_content&amp;id=914&amp;Itemid=489</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> Age UK Care in Crisis 2012</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> The Other Care Crisis</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">(2013)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">Leonard Cheshire Disability, National Autistic Society, </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333;